<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-519-462  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 519 462.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 14 1989 v23 n33 p67(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Easing paper flow could help slash DOD budget. (Department ofDefense) (includes related article on enabling technologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pechersky, Paul N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Department of Defense (DOD) is developing computer-aidedacquisition and logistics support (CALS), a system forelectronically exchanging technical product documentation withdefense contractors.andP;  CALS is a major cost-savings initiativedesigned to gradually replace paper-intensive developmentprocesses with highly automated methods, eliminating incompatible'islands' of automation.andP;  Automating documentation and providingtechnical data in electronic form is expected to increaseproductivity by 20 to 30 percent.andP;  CALS is likely to penetrate thecommercial arena because the DOD depends on virtually every USmanufacturing sector for material.andP;  The CALS system will eliminatethe need to input data into multiple data bases and reduce theeffort required to transfer design information to themanufacturing process.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseElectronic data interchangeStrategic PlanningDocumentationSupport ServicesDefense Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>